@NODE "CGWBPattern" "WARNING: CGWBPattern"

 @{B}[À @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MatWB 3.0 @{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1} Add-on package 2  @{BG BACKGROUND} À]@{UB}

 @{B}  À      @{U}WARNING: CGWBPATTERN@{UU}     À @{UB}

 I  have to warn  all  you people  out
 there  who are using  CGWBPattern.  I
 recently     bought      myself     a
 CyberVision64/3D graphics accelerator
 board.  After  the  installation  and
 proper configuration of the whole CGX
 package I noticed my chip memory.  It
 was  about 1.5 Mb just after a  boot.
 This is WAY beneath  the normal value
 when  you  use a  graphics board.  My
 friend also has a CV64/3D and  he has
 1.9 Mb  chip  after  a  boot.   So  I
 started  figuring  out  where I  lost
 those   400 Kb   of   chip   RAM.   I
 eventually  came 'round  to  checking
 CGWBPattern. When I removed the patch
 from my user-startup  I had my memory
 back,  but I didn't  have a  backdrop
 anymore.  So I  dug up the  WBPattern
 program that comes with "FastIPrefs",
 set the parameters and rebooted. BAM!
 There it was. Exactly the same amount
 of  chip  mem  as  my  friend  AND  a
 backdrop.  The only problem I now had
 was  the  fact  that  I had  no  more
 random                     backdrops.
 After scanning my Aminet Sets I found
 a program  called "MagicSelector".  I
 tried it and voilß!  Problems solved!
 I could  even remove the  "DarkSound"
 proggie from my  WBStartup drawer coz
 "MagicSelector" also  supports random
 sounds!    Neat    program    indeed.

 There    is    only    one    glitch:
 "MagicSelector"  is  somewhat an  old
 proggie and does  not support the new
 WBPattern   prefsfile   format   from
 "FastIPrefs". This means that you can
 not select the "precision" with which
 the  patterns will  be  remapped  and
 drawn.  You will NOT notice this with
 the 16 colour patterns from MatWB but
 if  you  intend  to  use  8/16/24 bit
 patterns  then   you're  fucked   cuz
 they're        fuckin'          ugly!

 If  you  want   "MagicSelector"  then
 search      the       Aminet      for
 "MagicSelV1_80.lha". I didn't include
 it in this archive  coz it's allready
 too                              big.

 If  anyone  knows  a  better   random
 backdrop and pattern selector, let me
 know via: crisp@unicall.be,  subject:
 "BETTER RANDOM  PATTERN SELECTOR  FOR
 MATWB".   Many   thanks  in  advance.

@ENDNODE

